Confluence currently is distributed with the default, serial garbage collector. 

This is known to be a performance bottleneck during peak periods as the single GC thread scouring the deterministic, directed object graph typically requires exclusive time on the CPU linear to the amount of memory allocated. Typically, a 2G system will require about 2 seconds. If we parallelize this, where N is cpu count, we can reduce this 'stop-the-world' event on contemporary systems to 1/4 or 1/8 or better of the original.

This bottleneck of cumulative memory debt is artificially approached as whilst the application is offline GC'ing, the underlying OS will continue to buffer incoming page requests via the OS level socket.

By having a serial collector it is making a bad situation worse, as users will typically hammer the installation when responsiveness suffers beyond a certain tolerance threshold, spawning new requests for the already overloaded installation to process.

The syntax to include in JAVA_OPTS is {{+XX:+UseParallelOldGC}}
Don't be confused with {{+XX:+UseParallelGC}}, which is just an explicit setting of the default serial collector for tenured.

We've already migrated some of the largest confluence installations via support tickets with excellent results; it would be beneficial for smaller instances to have that extra resiliency and agility during aggressively loaded circumstances.

