CONF-16108 (where the SQL macro cannot see a datasource resource when rendered via a SOAP call) occurs because the javax.naming.InitialContext created by the PluginsClassLoader doesn't have access to a datasource resource.

We need a way to expose these webapp resources without needing to hack the classloader - one option would be to create a Context provider class that exposes an implementation of the Context interface.

Then, client code could be injected with the provider and write:


{code}
String jndi = "java:comp/env/jdbc/" + dataSourceName;
DataSource ds = null;
Context ctx;
try {
    ctx = contextProvider.getContext();
    try {
        ds = (DataSource) ctx.lookup(jndi);
    }
{code}

instead of 
{code}
String jndi = "java:comp/env/jdbc/" + dataSourceName;
DataSource ds = null;
InitialContext ctx;
try {
    ctx = new InitialContext();
    try {
        ds = (DataSource) ctx.lookup(jndi);
    }
{code}

The Context provider would be able to filter out resources that shouldn't be accessible for security or stability reasons.

